Technical Specification for Social Architecture

Version 1.0 | Requirements Document
Project: Martian Settlement - Governance Integration Layer
Purpose: To translate the social and governance requirements of The Adaptive Constitution v2.0 into mandatory engineering and architectural specifications for habitat design.

---

1. Introduction & Design Philosophy

Habitat design is social design. On Mars, where every environment is constructed and "outside" is lethal, architecture directly determines psychological well-being and social stability. This document specifies the physical systems required to enable the settlement's governance processes, mitigate conflict, and manage edge-case failures.

Core Principle: The habitat must provide gradients of space, privacy, and sensory experience to support the full range of human social needs, from communal gathering to secure isolation.

2. Primary Habitat Zones & Requirements

The settlement's layout must move beyond pure efficiency to intentionally foster the social dynamics required for long-term viability.

Zone Constitutional Purpose Key Technical Specifications
Private Quarters Article II (Autonomy) - Sanctuary for individual identity and recovery. Minimum Volume: 25 m³ per person. Acoustic Isolation: Sound Transmission Class (STC) rating of 50+. Environmental Control: Individual light, temperature, and white noise control. Non-Monitorable: Strict exclusion from all communal sensor networks.
Neutral Mediation Pod Restorative Justice Protocol - A dedicated, neutral ground for facilitated conflict resolution. Location: Centrally located, equidistant from all living quarters. Configuration: Round table with 8 seats, neutral colors, no external branding or symbols. Technology: Dedicated, offline recording system; whiteboard surfaces. Rule: No personal comms or recording devices permitted inside.
The Commons Article III (Participation) - Space for unstructured social interaction and communal bonding. Design: High ceiling (≥4m), with visual connection to greenhouse or simulated vista. Flexibility: Reconfigurable furniture and partitions for different group sizes. Sensory Richness: Dynamic lighting that simulates Earth-like diurnal cycles, access to living plants, variable acoustic environments.
Facilitation Chamber Monthly/Annual Governance - Formal space for democratic processes. Layout: Semi-circular seating facing a public display, ensuring all participants can see each other. Voting System: Integrated, secure anonymous voting terminals at each seat. Transparency: Full audio-visual recording of all official proceedings, publicly archived.

3. The Palliative Separation Module (PSM)

This is a critical, non-negotiable system for implementing the Palliative Separation Protocol. It is neither a prison nor a medical bay, but a highly specialized life-support habitat for indefinite, dignified quarantine.

3.1. Core Design Principles

· Autonomy: Must sustain life independently for a minimum of 6 months.
· Dignity: Provides a high quality of life commensurate with settlement standards.
· Safety: Physically protects the settlement from intentional or accidental harm originating within the PSM.
· Observability: Allows for essential health and safety monitoring without two-way interaction.

3.2. Technical Specifications

System Requirement Justification
Structure & Location Detachable module connected via a double-door airlock vestibule to the main hab. Located at a terminus of the habitat spine. Allows for complete physical isolation. The airlock vestibule prevents atmospheric mixing and provides a buffer for supply transfer.
Life Support Fully redundant, closed-loop system (air, water, temperature) independent of primary settlement systems. 6-month minimum consumable buffer. Upholds the commitment to indefinite care. Prevents the individual's status from becoming a resource drain or tactical weapon.
Communication One-way audio/video feed from PSM to Medbay only. Text-based messaging system to Facilitation Committee, with delayed send/receive capability (e.g., 12-hour delay). Enables necessary health/safety monitoring while preventing real-time harassment or negotiation under duress. Delayed comms encourage reflection.
Supply & Care Dual-sided, pass-through airlock (like a bank teller drawer) for delivery of food, medicine, and supplies. No routine physical access. Fulfills duty of care without risking staff exposure to potential violence or psychological manipulation.
Internal Environment Equivalent in volume and amenities to a standard Private Quarter (25 m³), with enhanced VR/entertainment library and exercise capability. Preserves human dignity and mental well-being, making reintegration more likely.
Safety & Override External, manual hard override for life-support systems in event of module failure. No internal override capability. All tools and potential weapons excluded from standard supplies. The settlement has an obligation to prevent death, even of an individual in PSM, from a technical failure. This is a profound ethical commitment.

4. Sensory & Environmental Mediation Systems

To combat sensory monotony and support psychological health, the habitat must actively manage the internal environment.

System Requirement Governance Link
Dynamic Lighting Ceiling-wide panels capable of simulating full diurnal cycles (dawn, daylight, dusk, night) and seasonal variations in light temperature and intensity. Mitigates Sensory Monotony, regulates circadian rhythms.
Acoustic Environment Zone-controlled ambient sound systems offering selectable, non-looping soundscapes (e.g., forest, rainfall, café murmur, white noise). Provides auditory privacy and choice, reduces tension from constant mechanical noise.
Visual Variability High-resolution display walls in Commons and private quarters capable of displaying curated vistas (Earth landscapes, Martian terrain, abstract art). Counters visual starvation and confinement.
Olfactory Delivery Limited, safe scent dispersion system in Commons for occasional, scheduled release of non-allergenic scents (e.g., pine, soil, citrus). Triggers memory and positive emotional states, breaks chemical monotony of recycled air.

5. Implementation Phasing

These requirements must be integrated into the habitat design from the outset, but can be implemented in phases.

· Phase 1 (Initial Habs): Private Quarters, The Commons, and basic Sensory Systems (Dynamic Lighting) are mandatory for first crew. Location for future PSM must be pre-planned with connections.
· Phase 2 (First Expansion): Construction of dedicated Neutral Mediation Pod and Facilitation Chamber.
· Phase 3 (Pre-100 Population): PSM must be constructed and certified operational before permanent settlement population exceeds 50. This is a critical path item for social safety.

